{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"How do you feed a city?"},{"time":4000,"text":"It's one of the great questions of our time."},{"time":6000,"text":"Yet it's one that's rarely asked."},{"time":8000,"text":"We take it for granted that if we go into a shop"},{"time":11000,"text":"or restaurant, or indeed into this theater's foyer in about an hour's time,"},{"time":15000,"text":"there is going to be food there waiting for us,"},{"time":18000,"text":"having magically come from somewhere."}]},{"cues":[{"time":20000,"text":"But when you think that every day for a city the size of London,"},{"time":25000,"text":"enough food has to be produced,"},{"time":28000,"text":"transported, bought and sold,"},{"time":31000,"text":"cooked, eaten, disposed of,"},{"time":35000,"text":"and that something similar has to happen every day"},{"time":37000,"text":"for every city on earth,"},{"time":39000,"text":"it's remarkable that cities get fed at all."}]},{"cues":[{"time":42000,"text":"We live in places like this as if"},{"time":44000,"text":"they're the most natural things in the world,"},{"time":47000,"text":"forgetting that because we're animals"},{"time":49000,"text":"and that we need to eat,"},{"time":51000,"text":"we're actually as dependent on the natural world"},{"time":55000,"text":"as our ancient ancestors were."},{"time":57000,"text":"And as more of us move into cities,"},{"time":59000,"text":"more of that natural world is being"},{"time":62000,"text":"transformed into extraordinary landscapes like the one behind me --"},{"time":65000,"text":"it's soybean fields in Mato Grosso in Brazil --"},{"time":68000,"text":"in order to feed us."},{"time":71000,"text":"These are extraordinary landscapes,"},{"time":73000,"text":"but few of us ever get to see them."}]},{"cues":[{"time":75000,"text":"And increasingly these landscapes"},{"time":77000,"text":"are not just feeding us either."},{"time":79000,"text":"As more of us move into cities,"},{"time":81000,"text":"more of us are eating meat,"},{"time":83000,"text":"so that a third of the annual grain crop globally"},{"time":86000,"text":"now gets fed to animals"},{"time":88000,"text":"rather than to us human animals."},{"time":90000,"text":"And given that it takes three times as much grain --"},{"time":94000,"text":"actually ten times as much grain --"},{"time":96000,"text":"to feed a human if it's passed through an animal first,"},{"time":99000,"text":"that's not a very efficient way of feeding us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":104000,"text":"And it's an escalating problem too."},{"time":106000,"text":"By 2050, it's estimated that twice the number"},{"time":109000,"text":"of us are going to be living in cities."},{"time":111000,"text":"And it's also estimated that there is going to be twice as much"},{"time":113000,"text":"meat and dairy consumed."},{"time":115000,"text":"So meat and urbanism are rising hand in hand."},{"time":120000,"text":"And that's going to pose an enormous problem."},{"time":122000,"text":"Six billion hungry carnivores to feed,"},{"time":125000,"text":"by 2050."},{"time":129000,"text":"That's a big problem. And actually if we carry on as we are,"},{"time":131000,"text":"it's a problem we're very unlikely to be able to solve."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"Nineteen million hectares of rainforest are lost every year"},{"time":138000,"text":"to create new arable land."},{"time":140000,"text":"Although at the same time we're losing an equivalent amount"},{"time":143000,"text":"of existing arables to salinization and erosion."},{"time":147000,"text":"We're very hungry for fossil fuels too."},{"time":150000,"text":"It takes about 10 calories to produce every calorie"},{"time":153000,"text":"of food that we consume in the West."},{"time":157000,"text":"And even though there is food that we are producing at great cost,"},{"time":161000,"text":"we don't actually value it."},{"time":163000,"text":"Half the food produced in the USA is currently thrown away."},{"time":167000,"text":"And to end all of this, at the end of this long process,"},{"time":170000,"text":"we're not even managing to feed the planet properly."},{"time":173000,"text":"A billion of us are obese, while a further billion starve."},{"time":178000,"text":"None of it makes very much sense."}]},{"cues":[{"time":180000,"text":"And when you think that 80 percent of global trade in food now"},{"time":183000,"text":"is controlled by just five multinational corporations,"},{"time":188000,"text":"it's a grim picture."},{"time":190000,"text":"As we're moving into cities, the world is also embracing a Western diet."},{"time":193000,"text":"And if we look to the future,"},{"time":196000,"text":"it's an unsustainable diet."}]},{"cues":[{"time":198000,"text":"So how did we get here?"},{"time":200000,"text":"And more importantly, what are we going to do about it?"},{"time":203000,"text":"Well, to answer the slightly easier question first,"},{"time":207000,"text":"about 10,000 years ago, I would say,"},{"time":209000,"text":"is the beginning of this process"},{"time":211000,"text":"in the ancient Near East,"},{"time":213000,"text":"known as the Fertile Crescent."},{"time":215000,"text":"Because, as you can see, it was crescent shaped."},{"time":217000,"text":"And it was also fertile."},{"time":219000,"text":"And it was here, about 10,000 years ago,"},{"time":222000,"text":"that two extraordinary inventions,"},{"time":224000,"text":"agriculture and urbanism, happened"},{"time":227000,"text":"roughly in the same place and at the same time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":230000,"text":"This is no accident,"},{"time":232000,"text":"because agriculture and cities are bound together. They need each other."},{"time":236000,"text":"Because it was discovery of grain"},{"time":238000,"text":"by our ancient ancestors for the first time"},{"time":241000,"text":"that produced a food source that was large enough"},{"time":244000,"text":"and stable enough to support permanent settlements."},{"time":248000,"text":"And if we look at what those settlements were like,"},{"time":250000,"text":"we see they were compact."},{"time":252000,"text":"They were surrounded by productive farm land"},{"time":254000,"text":"and dominated by large temple complexes"},{"time":257000,"text":"like this one at Ur,"},{"time":259000,"text":"that were, in fact, effectively,"},{"time":261000,"text":"spiritualized, central food distribution centers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":264000,"text":"Because it was the temples that organized the harvest,"},{"time":267000,"text":"gathered in the grain, offered it to the gods,"},{"time":269000,"text":"and then offered the grain that the gods didn't eat back to the people."},{"time":273000,"text":"So, if you like,"},{"time":275000,"text":"the whole spiritual and physical life of these cities"},{"time":277000,"text":"was dominated by the grain and the harvest"},{"time":280000,"text":"that sustained them."},{"time":283000,"text":"And in fact, that's true of every ancient city."},{"time":286000,"text":"But of course not all of them were that small."},{"time":288000,"text":"Famously, Rome had about a million citizens"},{"time":291000,"text":"by the first century A.D."},{"time":293000,"text":"So how did a city like this feed itself?"},{"time":297000,"text":"The answer is what I call \"ancient food miles.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":300000,"text":"Basically, Rome had access to the sea,"},{"time":303000,"text":"which made it possible for it to import food from a very long way away."},{"time":306000,"text":"This is the only way it was possible to do this in the ancient world,"},{"time":309000,"text":"because it was very difficult to transport food over roads,"},{"time":312000,"text":"which were rough."},{"time":314000,"text":"And the food obviously went off very quickly."},{"time":316000,"text":"So Rome effectively waged war"},{"time":318000,"text":"on places like Carthage and Egypt"},{"time":321000,"text":"just to get its paws on their grain reserves."},{"time":323000,"text":"And, in fact, you could say that the expansion of the Empire"},{"time":326000,"text":"was really sort of one long, drawn out"},{"time":329000,"text":"militarized shopping spree, really."},{"time":331000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":333000,"text":"In fact -- I love the fact, I just have to mention this:"},{"time":335000,"text":"Rome in fact used to import oysters from London,"},{"time":338000,"text":"at one stage. I think that's extraordinary."}]},{"cues":[{"time":340000,"text":"So Rome shaped its hinterland"},{"time":343000,"text":"through its appetite."},{"time":345000,"text":"But the interesting thing is that the other thing also"},{"time":347000,"text":"happened in the pre-industrial world."},{"time":349000,"text":"If we look at a map of London in the 17th century,"},{"time":352000,"text":"we can see that its grain, which is coming in from the Thames,"},{"time":355000,"text":"along the bottom of this map."},{"time":357000,"text":"So the grain markets were to the south of the city."},{"time":360000,"text":"And the roads leading up from them"},{"time":362000,"text":"to Cheapside, which was the main market,"},{"time":364000,"text":"were also grain markets."}]},{"cues":[{"time":366000,"text":"And if you look at the name of one of those streets,"},{"time":368000,"text":"Bread Street, you can tell"},{"time":371000,"text":"what was going on there 300 years ago."},{"time":374000,"text":"And the same of course was true for fish."},{"time":376000,"text":"Fish was, of course, coming in by river as well. Same thing."},{"time":379000,"text":"And of course Billingsgate, famously, was London's fish market,"},{"time":382000,"text":"operating on-site here until the mid-1980s."},{"time":386000,"text":"Which is extraordinary, really, when you think about it."},{"time":388000,"text":"Everybody else was wandering around"},{"time":390000,"text":"with mobile phones that looked like bricks"},{"time":392000,"text":"and sort of smelly fish happening down on the port."}]},{"cues":[{"time":395000,"text":"This is another thing about food in cities:"},{"time":398000,"text":"Once its roots into the city are established,"},{"time":401000,"text":"they very rarely move."},{"time":403000,"text":"Meat is a very different story"},{"time":405000,"text":"because, of course, animals could walk into the city."},{"time":407000,"text":"So much of London's meat"},{"time":409000,"text":"was coming from the northwest,"},{"time":411000,"text":"from Scotland and Wales."},{"time":413000,"text":"So it was coming in, and arriving at the city at the northwest,"},{"time":416000,"text":"which is why Smithfield,"},{"time":418000,"text":"London's very famous meat market, was located up there."},{"time":421000,"text":"Poultry was coming in from East Anglia and so on, to the northeast."},{"time":425000,"text":"I feel a bit like a weather woman doing this. Anyway,"},{"time":426000,"text":"and so the birds were coming in"},{"time":430000,"text":"with their feet protected with little canvas shoes."},{"time":433000,"text":"And then when they hit the eastern end"},{"time":435000,"text":"of Cheapside, that's where they were sold,"},{"time":437000,"text":"which is why it's called Poultry."}]},{"cues":[{"time":439000,"text":"And, in fact, if you look at the map of any city"},{"time":442000,"text":"built before the industrial age,"},{"time":446000,"text":"you can trace food coming in to it."},{"time":448000,"text":"You can actually see how it was physically shaped by food,"},{"time":451000,"text":"both by reading the names of the streets, which give you a lot of clues."},{"time":454000,"text":"Friday Street, in a previous life,"},{"time":456000,"text":"is where you went to buy your fish on a Friday."},{"time":458000,"text":"But also you have to imagine it full of food."},{"time":460000,"text":"Because the streets and the public spaces"},{"time":463000,"text":"were the only places where food was bought and sold."}]},{"cues":[{"time":466000,"text":"And if we look at an image of Smithfield in 1830"},{"time":469000,"text":"you can see that it would have been very difficult to live in a city like this"},{"time":472000,"text":"and be unaware of where your food came from."},{"time":474000,"text":"In fact, if you were having Sunday lunch,"},{"time":476000,"text":"the chances were it was mooing or bleating outside your window"},{"time":478000,"text":"about three days earlier."},{"time":480000,"text":"So this was obviously an organic city,"},{"time":483000,"text":"part of an organic cycle."},{"time":486000,"text":"And then 10 years later everything changed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":489000,"text":"This is an image of the Great Western in 1840."},{"time":492000,"text":"And as you can see, some of the earliest train passengers"},{"time":494000,"text":"were pigs and sheep."},{"time":496000,"text":"So all of a sudden, these animals are no longer walking into market."},{"time":500000,"text":"They're being slaughtered out of sight and mind,"},{"time":502000,"text":"somewhere in the countryside."},{"time":504000,"text":"And they're coming into the city by rail."},{"time":506000,"text":"And this changes everything."},{"time":509000,"text":"To start off with, it makes it possible"},{"time":511000,"text":"for the first time to grow cities,"},{"time":512000,"text":"really any size and shape, in any place."},{"time":514000,"text":"Cities used to be constrained by geography;"},{"time":518000,"text":"they used to have to get their food through very difficult physical means."},{"time":521000,"text":"All of a sudden they are effectively emancipated from geography."}]},{"cues":[{"time":525000,"text":"And as you can see from these maps of London,"},{"time":528000,"text":"in the 90 years after the trains came,"},{"time":530000,"text":"it goes from being a little blob that was quite easy to feed"},{"time":534000,"text":"by animals coming in on foot, and so on,"},{"time":536000,"text":"to a large splurge,"},{"time":538000,"text":"that would be very, very difficult to feed with anybody on foot,"},{"time":541000,"text":"either animals or people."},{"time":544000,"text":"And of course that was just the beginning. After the trains came cars,"},{"time":547000,"text":"and really this marks the end of this process."},{"time":551000,"text":"It's the final emancipation of the city"},{"time":553000,"text":"from any apparent relationship with nature at all."}]},{"cues":[{"time":556000,"text":"And this is the kind of city that's devoid of smell,"},{"time":559000,"text":"devoid of mess, certainly devoid of people,"},{"time":561000,"text":"because nobody would have dreamed of walking in such a landscape."},{"time":564000,"text":"In fact, what they did to get food was they got in their cars,"},{"time":567000,"text":"drove to a box somewhere on the outskirts,"},{"time":570000,"text":"came back with a week's worth of shopping,"},{"time":572000,"text":"and wondered what on earth to do with it."},{"time":574000,"text":"And this really is the moment when our relationship,"},{"time":577000,"text":"both with food and cities, changes completely."}]},{"cues":[{"time":580000,"text":"Here we have food -- that used to be the center,"},{"time":583000,"text":"the social core of the city -- at the periphery."},{"time":586000,"text":"It used to be a social event, buying and selling food."},{"time":588000,"text":"Now it's anonymous."},{"time":590000,"text":"We used to cook; now we just add water,"},{"time":592000,"text":"or a little bit of an egg if you're making a cake or something."},{"time":597000,"text":"We don't smell food to see if it's okay to eat."},{"time":601000,"text":"We just read the back of a label on a packet."},{"time":604000,"text":"And we don't value food. We don't trust it."},{"time":607000,"text":"So instead of trusting it, we fear it."},{"time":609000,"text":"And instead of valuing it, we throw it away."}]},{"cues":[{"time":613000,"text":"One of the great ironies of modern food systems"},{"time":616000,"text":"is that they've made the very thing they promised"},{"time":618000,"text":"to make easier much harder."},{"time":620000,"text":"By making it possible to build cities anywhere and any place,"},{"time":624000,"text":"they've actually distanced us from our most important relationship,"},{"time":628000,"text":"which is that of us and nature."},{"time":631000,"text":"And also they've made us dependent on systems that only they can deliver,"},{"time":634000,"text":"that, as we've seen, are unsustainable."}]},{"cues":[{"time":636000,"text":"So what are we going to do about that?"},{"time":639000,"text":"It's not a new question."},{"time":641000,"text":"500 years ago it's what Thomas More was asking himself."},{"time":645000,"text":"This is the frontispiece of his book \"Utopia.\""},{"time":648000,"text":"And it was a series of semi-independent city-states,"},{"time":651000,"text":"if that sounds remotely familiar,"},{"time":653000,"text":"a day's walk from one another where everyone was basically farming-mad,"},{"time":656000,"text":"and grew vegetables in their back gardens,"},{"time":658000,"text":"and ate communal meals together, and so on."},{"time":660000,"text":"And I think you could argue that"},{"time":662000,"text":"food is a fundamental ordering principle of Utopia,"},{"time":665000,"text":"even though More never framed it that way."}]},{"cues":[{"time":668000,"text":"And here is another very famous \"Utopian\" vision,"},{"time":671000,"text":"that of Ebenezer Howard, \"The Garden City.\""},{"time":673000,"text":"Same idea: series of semi-independent city-states,"},{"time":676000,"text":"little blobs of metropolitan stuff with arable land around,"},{"time":680000,"text":"joined to one another by railway."},{"time":682000,"text":"And again, food could be said to be"},{"time":684000,"text":"the ordering principle of his vision."},{"time":687000,"text":"It even got built, but nothing to do with"},{"time":689000,"text":"this vision that Howard had."},{"time":691000,"text":"And that is the problem with these Utopian ideas,"},{"time":694000,"text":"that they are Utopian."}]},{"cues":[{"time":696000,"text":"Utopia was actually a word that Thomas Moore used deliberately."},{"time":699000,"text":"It was a kind of joke, because it's got a double derivation from the Greek."},{"time":703000,"text":"It can either mean a good place, or no place."},{"time":705000,"text":"Because it's an ideal. It's an imaginary thing. We can't have it."},{"time":709000,"text":"And I think, as a conceptual tool"},{"time":711000,"text":"for thinking about the very deep problem of human dwelling,"},{"time":714000,"text":"that makes it not much use."},{"time":716000,"text":"So I've come up with an alternative,"},{"time":719000,"text":"which is Sitopia, from the ancient Greek,"},{"time":722000,"text":"\"sitos\" for food, and \"topos\" for place."}]},{"cues":[{"time":724000,"text":"I believe we already live in Sitopia."},{"time":726000,"text":"We live in a world shaped by food,"},{"time":729000,"text":"and if we realize that, we can use food as a really powerful tool --"},{"time":732000,"text":"a conceptual tool, design tool, to shape the world differently."},{"time":736000,"text":"So if we were to do that, what might Sitopia look like?"},{"time":741000,"text":"Well I think it looks a bit like this."},{"time":743000,"text":"I have to use this slide. It's just the look on the face of the dog."},{"time":745000,"text":"But anyway, this is -- (Laughter)"},{"time":748000,"text":"it's food at the center of life,"},{"time":750000,"text":"at the center of family life, being celebrated,"},{"time":752000,"text":"being enjoyed, people taking time for it."},{"time":754000,"text":"This is where food should be in our society."}]},{"cues":[{"time":757000,"text":"But you can't have scenes like this unless you have people like this."},{"time":762000,"text":"By the way, these can be men as well."},{"time":764000,"text":"It's people who think about food,"},{"time":767000,"text":"who think ahead, who plan,"},{"time":769000,"text":"who can stare at a pile of raw vegetables"},{"time":771000,"text":"and actually recognize them."},{"time":773000,"text":"We need these people. We're part of a network."},{"time":776000,"text":"Because without these kinds of people we can't have places like this."},{"time":779000,"text":"Here, I deliberately chose this because it is a man buying a vegetable."},{"time":782000,"text":"But networks, markets where food is being grown locally."},{"time":786000,"text":"It's common. It's fresh."},{"time":788000,"text":"It's part of the social life of the city."},{"time":790000,"text":"Because without that, you can't have this kind of place,"},{"time":793000,"text":"food that is grown locally and also is part of the landscape,"},{"time":796000,"text":"and is not just a zero-sum commodity"},{"time":798000,"text":"off in some unseen hell-hole."},{"time":800000,"text":"Cows with a view."},{"time":802000,"text":"Steaming piles of humus."},{"time":804000,"text":"This is basically bringing the whole thing together."}]},{"cues":[{"time":807000,"text":"And this is a community project"},{"time":809000,"text":"I visited recently in Toronto."},{"time":811000,"text":"It's a greenhouse, where kids get told"},{"time":813000,"text":"all about food and growing their own food."},{"time":816000,"text":"Here is a plant called Kevin, or maybe it's a"},{"time":819000,"text":"plant belonging to a kid called Kevin. I don't know."},{"time":821000,"text":"But anyway, these kinds of projects"},{"time":824000,"text":"that are trying to reconnect us with nature is extremely important."}]},{"cues":[{"time":828000,"text":"So Sitopia, for me, is really a way of seeing."},{"time":830000,"text":"It's basically recognizing that Sitopia"},{"time":834000,"text":"already exists in little pockets everywhere."},{"time":836000,"text":"The trick is to join them up,"},{"time":838000,"text":"to use food as a way of seeing."},{"time":841000,"text":"And if we do that, we're going to stop seeing cities"},{"time":844000,"text":"as big, metropolitan, unproductive blobs, like this."},{"time":847000,"text":"We're going to see them more like this,"},{"time":849000,"text":"as part of the productive, organic framework"},{"time":852000,"text":"of which they are inevitably a part,"},{"time":854000,"text":"symbiotically connected."},{"time":856000,"text":"But of course, that's not a great image either,"},{"time":858000,"text":"because we need not to be producing food like this anymore."},{"time":861000,"text":"We need to be thinking more about permaculture,"},{"time":863000,"text":"which is why I think this image just"},{"time":865000,"text":"sums up for me the kind of thinking we need to be doing."},{"time":867000,"text":"It's a re-conceptualization"},{"time":869000,"text":"of the way food shapes our lives."}]},{"cues":[{"time":872000,"text":"The best image I know of this is from 650 years ago."},{"time":875000,"text":"It's Ambrogio Lorenzetti's \"Allegory of Good Government.\""},{"time":878000,"text":"It's about the relationship between the city and the countryside."},{"time":881000,"text":"And I think the message of this is very clear."},{"time":884000,"text":"If the city looks after the country,"},{"time":886000,"text":"the country will look after the city."},{"time":888000,"text":"And I want us to ask now,"},{"time":890000,"text":"what would Ambrogio Lorenzetti paint"},{"time":893000,"text":"if he painted this image today?"},{"time":895000,"text":"What would an allegory of good government look like today?"},{"time":898000,"text":"Because I think it's an urgent question."},{"time":900000,"text":"It's one we have to ask,"},{"time":902000,"text":"and we have to start answering."},{"time":904000,"text":"We know we are what we eat."},{"time":907000,"text":"We need to realize that the world is also what we eat."},{"time":909000,"text":"But if we take that idea, we can use food"},{"time":911000,"text":"as a really powerful tool to shape the world better."},{"time":915000,"text":"Thank you very much."},{"time":917000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}